capabilities of some computers. Using the substructuring technique, one can build the FEA model for each subsystem first (such as the cab, chassis, steering system, suspension system, payload, and so on) and then condense the FEA equations to smaller ones relating only DOFs on the interfaces between the subsystems and residing on a residual structure (e.g., the chassis). The condensed system is much smaller than the original system and can be solved readily.

Figure 4.3. An FEA model of a truck analyzed using substructures.
The advantages of using the substructuring technique are: โข Good for large problems (which will otherwise exceed your computer capabilities) โข Less CPU time per run once the superelements have been processed (i.e., matrices have
been condensed and saved) โข Components may be modeled by different groups โข Partial redesign requires only partial reanalysis (reduced cost) โข Efficient for problems with local nonlinearities (such as confined plastic deformations)
which can be placed in one superelement (residual structure) โข Exact for static deformation and stress analysis
The disadvantages of using the substructuring technique are: โข Increased overhead for file management โข Increased initial time for setting up the system โข Matrix condensations for dynamic problems introduce new approximations

